      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Model setup, boundary condition application, and post-processing were independently reviewed by a second analyst at each participating organization. Documented checklists and peer-review records confirm Gradation 2 use-error controls were applied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic isotropic material models are used for titanium alloy components; contact is modeled with penalty-based formulation. The model form is well-established for metallic spinal implant constructs under quasi-static loading and is consistent with the physics of ASTM F1717 testing. Literature precedent and prior FDA assessments support Gradation 3 adequacy."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, Poisson ratio) were sourced from certified material test reports for the specific Ti-6Al-4V alloy lot used in the physical constructs. Geometry was derived from calibrated CMM measurements of the actual test specimens. Friction coefficients were taken from published tribological data for titanium-on-UHMWPE interfaces and subjected to sensitivity analysis."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "N=11 physical constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens were from the same production lot and were dimensionally characterized prior to testing. Sample size is sufficient for Gradation 3 given the low coefficient of variation observed in experimental results (CV < 5%)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single load configuration (compression-bending at 5 degrees) per ASTM F1717. Only one test condition was evaluated; no variation in angulation, load magnitude range, or temperature was introduced. This limits the achieved level to Gradation 2, which falls below the required Gradation 3. This shortfall is documented and accepted given the regulatory precedent for single-condition F1717 testing in 510(k) submissions."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "A formal parameter equivalency table was constructed mapping each physical test parameter (specimen geometry, fixture stiffness, loading rate, grip torque) to its FEA counterpart. All parameters were demonstrated to be equivalent within measurement uncertainty bounds, satisfying Gradation 3 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and failure load predictions from all three FEA models were compared against experimental measurements using both graphical overlay and quantitative metrics (mean percent error, 95% prediction interval coverage). Mean percent error in stiffness was 4.2% across all models and specimens, within the pre-specified 10% acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and failure load are the primary quantities of interest for regulatory assessment of spinal implant mechanical performance under ASTM F1717. These quantities are directly linked to the clinical decision context of evaluating implant structural adequacy under physiological loading, confirming Gradation 3 relevance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
